 Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Kimberley, Forehoe, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bellinger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): dissimilated form of   Berringer  . Compare   Benninger  .","German: habitational name for someone from a place called Belling or Bellingen (see   Belling  ). It is also found in France (Lorraine).","Americanized form of French <b>Bélanger</b> (see   Belanger  ) or of its variant   Bellanger  . Compare   Ballinger   2 and   Bellenger   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Berringer","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Berenger</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Beringar</i>, <i>Barengar</i>, composed of the elements <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’ + <i>gair</i> ‘spear’. The surname has several variants, including   Beringer  ,   Barringer  , and   Banger  , as well as the dissimilated forms   Bellanger  ,   Bellinger  ,   Ballanger  , and   Ballinger  , where /l/ has been substituted for /r/. The personal name <i>Berenger</i> was well known in England in the 12th and 13th centuries, having been borne by one of the paladins in the widely popular Charlemagne romances.","German: variant of   Beringer  .","Americanized form of German   Boehringer  ."]},{"name":"Ballenger","meanings":["English (of Norman origin; Gloucestershire): variant of   Bellinger   (see also   Ballinger  ). Compare   Ballanger   2 and   Bellenger   2.","French: variant of   Bellanger   1 and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this. This form of the surname is almost extinct in France. Compare   Ballanger   1 and   Bellenger   1."]}]},{"name":"Elinor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":7,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":42,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":73,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Elinor Bellinger was born about 1217, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Jacob Bellinger, was 31 and her mother, Margaret Bowman, was 28. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Lord Guy de Botetourte. She died on 20 January 1297, in England, at the age of 81."},"et":{"about 1217–20 January 1297":"umbes 1217–20. jaanuar 1297","1217–1297":"1217–1297","1214–1264":"1214–1264","1235–1316":"1235–1316","1240–1290":"1240–1290","1188–Male":"1188–Surnud","1191–Female":"1191–Surnud","20 January 1297":"2